50|$|<b>Andorrans,</b> who are ethnically Catalans, are a {{minority}} in their own country; Spanish, French, and Portuguese residents make up 67.7% of the population.|$|R
5|$|From 1996 until 2014 Andorra {{played their}} home matches at the Comunal d'Andorra la Vella, {{in the capital}} city of Andorra la Vella. This stadium has a {{capacity}} of 1,800 and also hosts the matches of club sides FC Andorra and the <b>Andorran</b> Premier League. On 9 September 2014, the national team began playing at the new Estadi Nacional with a capacity of 3,306.|$|E
25|$|There {{are three}} systems of school—Andorran, French, and Spanish—which use Catalan, French, and Spanish, respectively, {{as the main}} {{language}} of instruction. Parents may choose which system their children attend. All schools are built and maintained by <b>Andorran</b> authorities, but teachers in the French and Spanish schools are paid {{for the most part}} by France and Spain. About 50% of <b>Andorran</b> children attend the French primary schools, and the rest attend Spanish or <b>Andorran</b> schools.|$|E
25|$|The {{historic}} and official language is Catalan, a Romance language. The <b>Andorran</b> government encourages {{the use of}} Catalan. It funds a Commission for Catalan Toponymy in Andorra (Catalan: la Comissió de Toponímia d'Andorra), and provides free Catalan classes to assist immigrants. <b>Andorran</b> television and radio stations use Catalan.|$|E
50|$|Among other Latin peoples we {{can also}} find the Valencians, the Aragonese people, the <b>Andorrans,</b> the Balearic people, the Maltese people and the Romansh people.|$|R
50|$|Article 21 covers {{movement}} within Andorra, {{and exit}} from and {{entry to the}} national territory. Also, it gives <b>Andorrans,</b> and established foreign nationals, {{the right to make}} their home in Andorra.|$|R
50|$|Article 20 covers education. This is {{guaranteed}} all <b>Andorrans,</b> and moreover, parents {{have the right}} to choose what kind of education that their children will have, in keeping with their own religious convictions.|$|R
25|$|An expert jury {{chose the}} three best songs {{to compete at}} the 2009 <b>Andorran</b> Eurovision {{national}} final. Interested singers were told to send demos with a maximum of three songs, {{with at least one}} song sung in Catalan. In addition, composers were told to send in at least one song to the station. All composers and singers must be over 18, preferably with <b>Andorran</b> citizenship and nationality. Catalan lyrics are preferred by RTVA. The singers' musical experience and fluency in Catalan, as well as their fluency in speaking English and French, will also be taken into account. At the national final, the <b>Andorran</b> entrant will be chosen entirely through the use of SMS texting by the public.|$|E
25|$|Georgi {{failed to}} reach the final {{becoming}} the sixth <b>Andorran</b> Eurovision entrant to miss the grand final.|$|E
25|$|Immediately after retiring, 34-year-old Saviola was {{appointed}} assistant manager at FC Ordino in the <b>Andorran</b> Primera Divisió.|$|E
